<collectingCountry id="F344C28EFFCD323A1B432246FE0026D9" box="[362,429,621,647]" name="China" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="49974CFCFFCD323A1B922246FDBA26D9" box="[443,535,621,647]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C349D195FFCD323A1AEE22BAFBF526F5" box="[199,1112,657,683]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BEC821EFFCD323A1AEE22BAFBF526F5" blockId="6.[151,1437,152,791]" box="[199,1112,657,683]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">
<emphasis id="B9275E0CFFCD323A1AEE22BAFEE326F5" bold="true" box="[199,334,657,683]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a combination of Latin terms 
<emphasis id="B9275E0CFFCD323A19B722BAFC7C26F5" box="[926,977,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">pub-</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B9275E0CFFCD323A1E2122B9FBFC26F5" box="[1032,1105,658,683]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">pennis</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C349D195FFCD323A1AEE229FFD1A2749" pageId="6" pageNumber="357" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BEC821EFFCD323A1AEE229FFD1A2749" blockId="6.[151,1437,152,791]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">
<emphasis id="B9275E0CFFCD323A1AEE229FFEEF2691" bold="true" box="[199,322,692,719]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species shares a similar dorsal color pattern with 
<taxonomicName id="4C53F99DFFCD323A19DA229DFAA42691" authority="Weise" authorityName="Weise, H" authorityYear="1889" box="[1011,1289,693,719]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Exomis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="357" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="peplopteroides">
<emphasis id="B9275E0CFFCD323A19DA229DFB142691" box="[1011,1209,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">E. peplopteroides</emphasis>
Weise
</taxonomicName>
, but the new species can be well defined by the elytra clothed with short pale pubescence and by the aedeagus with the basal 3/4 paler and less sclerotized than the apical quarter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
